Reference-contexts: Booth, a Nuffield Fellow in the Physics Department at Birkbeck College in the University of London, discussed the possibility of using electronic computing devices to translate human languages <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. In 1949 Weaver wrote a memorandum entitled Translation that was distributed to leaders in the computing field. In this memo he expanded on his idea of using computers to translate human languages. <p> As a result of this conference an MT project was started at Georgetown University by Leon Dostert. The goal of this project was to demonstrate the feasibility of MT. IBM became a collaborator with Georgetown soon after the research group was formed <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. On January 7, 1954 the Georgetown - IBM team demonstrated its Russian to English translation system. The translation program was very small. It had a vocabulary of 250 Russian words, 6 grammar rules, and very carefully selected Russian text. <p> The demonstration was repeated several times, including once to D.Y. Panov of the USSR Academy of Sciences later that same year. Upon his return MT research began in earnest in the Soviet Union <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. 4.2 1954 - 1964 Soon after the Georgetown - IBM demonstration MT research expanded greatly both in the USA and abroad. There was a mood of considerable optimism in the field, with a feeling that imminent success was just around the corner. <p> The other camp, made up of groups such as those at MIT, Harvard, RAND, and Berkeley, believed that it was important to understand the underlying linguistic theories before proceeding on to the development of actual systems <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. In June, 1960 MT research in the USA was given government endorsement with a report compiled by the Committee on Science and Astronautics of the US House of Representatives. <p> the Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in 1964, and the Georgetown Automatic Translation (GAT) Russian to English system that had been installed at two locations: the Atomic Energy Commission at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory in 1964 and for the European Atomic Energy Community (EUROTOM) Center at Ispra, Italy in 1963 <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. These two systems employed fairly simple word for word replacement methodologies. There were no underlying linguistic theories. GAT, for instance, was developed for specific texts, and then modified for another text, and so on (Slocum 1985). <p> The TL text synthesized by GAT and Mark II required extensive post- editing. However, even unedited target text was often judged satisfactory by clients of the GAT system who had the choice between the MT produced text and no translations at all <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. It was clear that neither the operational nor the theoretical groups had achieved the successes that they had felt were so close at hand. While much progress had been made in linguistic research it was apparent that the problems of translation were far more complex than first expected. <p> However, there are significant improvements in the software design techniques. Rather than being implemented as a huge monolithic program as GAT was, Systran takes advantage of modular design techniques. As a result it is much easier to maintain and modify <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. During this decade Systran was installed at numerous sites. In July 1970 Systran took over from the IBM Mark II at the USAF's Foreign Technology Division. <p> Systran was used by the National Aeronautic and Space Administration (NASA) during the joint Apollo Soyuz space mission between the USA and USSR 7 in 1974 - 75. In 1976 Systran replaced the GAT system at EURATOM <ref> (Hutchins 1986) </ref>. In 1978 Xerox selected five Systran language pairs for installation. 4.4.2 TAUM METEO MT research in Canada began in the mid-sixties.
