Reference-contexts: In addition, it would be difficult to justify the expense of developing an MT system to deal with literary works since there is no shortage of literary translators <ref> (Slocum 1985) </ref>. MT systems must use procedural methods. Text that involves many pragmatic meanings and must use units of translation greater than a sentence is too complex to translate procedurally. MT systems should confine themselves to texts that do not reach this level of meaning. <p> To date, all operational MT systems have concerned themselves with scientific, technical, or bureaucratic texts. This is due to the fact that these are areas that rely less on pragmatic meanings to convey their points and that these are the areas that have the greatest demand for translation <ref> (Slocum 1985 and JEIDA 1989) </ref>. 3 Survey of MT Concepts 3.1 Categories of MT Systems Slocum (1985) describes the three generally accepted categories of MT systems. Fully Automated High Quality Translation (FAHQT), Machine Aided Translation (MAT), and Terminology Data Bases represent successively lower capabilities of MT systems. <p> These two systems employed fairly simple word for word replacement methodologies. There were no underlying linguistic theories. GAT, for instance, was developed for specific texts, and then modified for another text, and so on <ref> (Slocum 1985) </ref>. The TL text synthesized by GAT and Mark II required extensive post- editing. However, even unedited target text was often judged satisfactory by clients of the GAT system who had the choice between the MT produced text and no translations at all (Hutchins 1986). <p> The appeal of translating weather forecasts was that the language and vocabulary used is very limited. This made it well suited for MT and terribly dull for the human translator. It was so monotonous a task that the average tenure of a translator was only 6 months <ref> (Slocum 1985) </ref>. Development of the MT system METEO began in May 1975. By May 1977 the transfer based MT system was operational. METEO is the only fully automatic MT system in operation in the world. It operates 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. <p> Siemens of West Germany has developed a large German to English system called METAL that is now available commercially. METAL was begun in 1961 at the University of Texas and was taken over by Siemens in 1980 <ref> (Slocum 1985) </ref>. The Translation Bureau of the West German Government is developing a large on-line dictionary for technical terms called LEXIS (JEIDA 1989).
